>.','none'),(2607,'','default','Below is a list of all the content types on your site. All posts that exist on your site are instances of one of these content types.','6.22'),(2608,'','default','To create a new content type, enter the human-readable name, the machine-readable name, and all other relevant fields that are on this page. Once created, users of your site will be able to create posts that are instances of this content type.','none'),(2609,'','default','The revisions let you track differences between multiple versions of a post.','none'),(2610,'','default','<h1 class=\"title\">Welcome to your new Drupal website!</h1><p>Please follow these steps to set up and start using your website:</p>','6.22'),(2611,'','default','<strong>Configure your website</strong> Once logged in, visit the <a href=\"@admin\">administration section</a>, where you can <a href=\"@config\">customize and configure</a> all aspects of your website.','6.22'),(2612,'','default','<strong>Enable additional functionality</strong> Next, visit the <a href=\"@modules\">module list</a> and enable features which suit your specific needs. You can find additional modules in the <a href=\"@download_modules\">Drupal modules download section</a>.','6.22'),(2613,'','default','<strong>Customize your website design</strong> To change the \"look and feel\" of your website, visit the <a href=\"@themes\">themes section</a>. You may choose from one of the included themes or download additional themes from the <a href=\"@download_themes\">Drupal themes download section</a>.','6.22'),(2614,'','default','<strong>Start posting content</strong> Finally, you can <a href=\"@content\">create content</a> for your website. This message will disappear once you have promoted a post to the front page.','6.22'),(2615,'','default','Rebuilding content access permissions','none'),(2616,'','default','Content permissions have been rebuilt.','none'),(2617,'','default','The content access permissions have not been properly rebuilt.','none'),(2618,'','default','Allows content to be submitted to the site and displayed on pages.','none'),(2619,'','default','This site supports <a href=\"@openid-net\">OpenID</a>, a secure way to log into many websites using a single username and password. OpenID can reduce the necessity of managing many usernames and passwords for many websites.','none'),(2620,'','default','To use OpenID you must first establish an identity on a public or private OpenID server. If you do not have an OpenID and would like one, look into one of the <a href=\"@openid-providers\">free public providers</a>. You can find out more about OpenID at <a href=\"@openid-net\">this website</a>.','none'),(2621,'','default','If you already have an OpenID, enter the URL to your OpenID server below (e.g. myusername.openidprovider.com). Next time you login, you will be able to use this URL instead of a regular username and password. You can have multiple OpenID servers if you like; just keep adding them here.','none'),(2622,'','default','OpenID is a secure method for logging into many websites with a single username and password. It does not require special software, and it does not share passwords with any site to which it is associated; including your site.','none'),(2623,'','default','Users can create accounts using their OpenID, assign one or more OpenIDs to an existing account, and log in using an OpenID. This lowers the barrier to registration, which is good for the site, and offers convenience and security to the users. OpenID is not a trust system, so email verification is still necessary. The benefit stems from the fact that users can have a single password that they can use on many websites. This means they can easily update their single password from a centralized location, rather than having to change dozens of passwords individually.','none'),(2624,'','default','The basic concept is as follows: A user has an account on an OpenID server. This account provides them with a unique URL (such as myusername.openidprovider.com). When the user comes to your site, they are presented with the option of entering this URL. Your site then communicates with the OpenID server, asking it to verify the identity of the user. If the user is logged into their OpenID server, the server communicates back to your site, verifying the user. If they are not logged in, the OpenID server will ask the user for their password. At no point does your site record, or need to record the user\'s password.','none'),(2625,'','default','More information on OpenID is available at <a href=\"@openid-net\">OpenID.net</a>.','none'),(2626,'','default','For more information, see the online handbook entry for <a href=\"@handbook\">OpenID module</a>.','none'),(2627,'','default','Allows users to log into your site using OpenID.','none'),(2628,'','default','No URL aliases found.','none'),(2629,'','default','No URL aliases available.','none'),(2630,'','default','Update alias','none'),(2631,'','default','Create new alias','none'),(2632,'','default','The alias %alias is already in use in this language.','none'),(2633,'','default','The alias has been saved.','none'),(2634,'','default','Are you sure you want to delete path alias %title?','none'),(2635,'','default','Filter aliases','none'),(2636,'','default','The path module allows you to specify aliases for Drupal URLs. Such aliases improve readability of URLs for your users and may help internet search engines to index your content more effectively. More than one alias may be created for a given page.','none'),(2637,'','default','<p>Some examples of URL aliases are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>user/login =&gt; login</li>\n<li>image/tid/16 =&gt; store</li>\n<li>taxonomy/term/7+19+20+21 =&gt; store/products/whirlygigs</li>\n<li>node/3 =&gt; contact</li>\n</ul>\n','none'),(2638,'','default','The path module enables appropriately permissioned users to specify an optional alias in all node input and editing forms, and provides an interface to view and edit all URL aliases. The two permissions related to URL aliasing are <em>administer url aliases</em> and <em>create url aliases</em>. ','none'),(2639,'','default','This module also provides user-defined mass URL aliasing capabilities, which is useful if you wish to uniformly use URLs different from the default. For example, you may want to have your URLs presented in a different language. Access to the Drupal source code on the web server is required to set up mass URL aliasing. ','none'),(2640,'','default','For more information, see the online handbook entry for <a href=\"@path\">Path module</a>.','none'),(2641,'','default','Drupal provides complete control over URLs through aliasing, which is often used to make URLs more readable or easy to remember. For example, the alias \'about\' may be mapped onto the post at the system path \'node/1\', creating a more meaningful URL. Each system path can have multiple aliases.','none'),(2642,'','default','Enter the path you wish to create the alias for, followed by the name of the new alias.','none'),(2643,'','default','The alias has been deleted.','none'),(2644,'','default','The path is already in use.','none'),(2645,'','default','Allows users to rename URLs.','none'),(2646,'','default','The PHP filter adds the ability to include PHP code in posts. PHP is a general-purpose scripting language widely-used for web development; the content management system used by this website has been developed using PHP.','none'),(2647,'','default','Through the PHP filter, users with the proper permission may include custom PHP code within a page of the site. While this is a powerful and flexible feature if used by a trusted user with PHP experience, it is a significant and dangerous security risk in the hands of a malicious user. Even a trusted user may accidentally compromise the site by entering malformed or incorrect PHP code. Only the most trusted users should be granted permission to use the PHP filter, and all PHP code added through the PHP filter s